properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow accompanied by high winds will affect the community of Salluit today. Conditions will deteriorate throughout the morning and visibilities will be reduced to near zero under the snow and in the blowing snow beginning around midday. properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard conditions will develop near White Pass today. A strong frontal system will move across southwestern Yukon today bringing snow and strong winds. Most of the South Klondike Highway will see periods of snow and blowing snow with the worst conditions expected to be by the border at White Pass. Visibilities in snow and blowing snow will be below 400 metres. Blizzard conditions will ease overnight. Local blowing snow will continue into Thursday morning. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:

The conditions will ease early Thursday morning as the system weakens. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Brief but intense snowfall with blowing snow expected overnight tonight and Thursday morning. Total snowfall: 5 to 15 cm, with locally higher amounts possible. Wind gusts: up to 70 km/h Locations: Cape Breton Island and eastern Mainland Nova Scotia. Time span: overnight tonight into Thursday morning. Remarks: A short period of heavy snow accompanied by strong northerly winds and blowing snow is forecast to move over eastern Nova Scotia overnight tonight into Thursday morning. Heavy snowfall rates of several centimetres per hour and blowing snow will combine to give poor visibilities at times. Conditions will improve later Thursday morning as the system responsible moves offshore. At present, it is expected that the Sydney Metro and Cape Breton County region may avoid the heaviest snow and strong winds, but this could change if the track of the system and associated heavier snow bands shifts further to the east. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-30T11:38:59-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2020-01-29T19:39:59-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.0623080904.2020

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. A strong frontal system will continue to give heavy snow to the Haines Road from Haines Junction to Pleasant Camp today. Additional snowfall accumulations of 15 cm are expected by this evening. At the same time, strong southerly winds associated with the storm in combination with the heavy snow will produce blowing snow and reduced visibilities. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A low over the Gulf of Alaska will move into Yukon this afternoon. Winds will ease this evening as the low moves away. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. Rain and freezing rain is falling from Slave Lake to Wabamun and is moving eastwards at 45 km/h. This is a relatively narrow band of precipitation however it is forecast to expand as it moves eastwards. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. There may be a significant impact on rush hour traffic in urban areas. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.
